01:00:48.370 --> 01:00:51.890 align:middle line:84%
Hopefully I have the right to
buy things from someone else,

01:00:51.890 --> 01:00:53.920 align:middle line:90%
but only if they want the coin.

01:00:53.920 --> 01:00:57.070 align:middle line:84%
So my problem is
defined as in a network.

01:00:57.070 --> 01:00:59.020 align:middle line:90%
If I'm a buyer, I want sellers.

01:00:59.020 --> 01:01:01.120 align:middle line:90%
If I'm a seller, I want buyers.

01:01:01.120 --> 01:01:05.330 align:middle line:84%
My utility is a consequence of
who else is on the platform,

01:01:05.330 --> 01:01:08.930 align:middle line:84%
whether it's a cryptocurrency
platform or something else.

01:01:08.930 --> 01:01:11.830 align:middle line:84%
So there's a natural
externality here

01:01:11.830 --> 01:01:13.930 align:middle line:84%
that these households
care about who else

01:01:13.930 --> 01:01:16.240 align:middle line:90%
is populating the platform.

01:01:16.240 --> 01:01:18.220 align:middle line:84%
You would think
with an externality,

01:01:18.220 --> 01:01:20.630 align:middle line:84%
competitive equilibrium
is going to go bad

01:01:20.630 --> 01:01:23.290 align:middle line:84%
and we're not going to
get to a Pareto optimum,

01:01:23.290 --> 01:01:25.870 align:middle line:84%
but there is a
remedy, and that is

01:01:25.870 --> 01:01:29.930 align:middle line:84%
to price the right to
participate in the platform

01:01:29.930 --> 01:01:33.040 align:middle line:84%
according to your
agent utility type.

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:36.190 align:middle line:84%
So different types
pay different amounts.

01:01:36.190 --> 01:01:39.760 align:middle line:84%
They buy the rights to
participate on the platform,

01:01:39.760 --> 01:01:43.270 align:middle line:84%
and that's going to
internalize the externality,

01:01:43.270 --> 01:01:45.010 align:middle line:84%
